1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ @@HeaderStart@@The Evans Gambit:@@HeaderEnd@@- White sacrifices a pawn for a lead in development, more space, and attack on the black king    As a principle, White does not want to trade pieces because it diminishes his attacking chances  - In all accepted Evans Gambit variations, we play first d4 and then O-O  - We play Qb3 before O-O if an attack on f7 is hard to defend   Typical ideas:  - ♕b3 with an attack on f7   - ♗a3 with control of the a3-f8 diagonal   - pawn breaks with d4-d5 or e4-e5   Tactical motifs:  - ♗xf7 followed by ♕d5+ with a double attack on Kf7 and Bc5  - after d5 chasing Nc6 away -a double attack with Qa4+ or Qb5+ on Ke8 and Ba5  - chasing and trapping the black queen }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Bc5
{ On Lichess  (Rapid and Classical games, all ratings)  5... Ba5 and 5... Bc5 are equally popular and played in 35-40% of all the games. Together they cover more than 75% of the games played with the Accepted Evans Gambit. 5... Ba5 is a slightly better move as after 5... Bc5, White can play d4 and attack Bc5 with tempo. }
6. d4 { d4 first and later O-O in all variations! } 6... exd4 7. O-O dxc3
{ A common mistake. This allows a double attack. } 8. Bxf7+
{ Not the immediate double attack with   8.Qd5  as  8...Qe7  defends both Bc5 and pawn f7.    White scores 74% versus Black 23% }
8... Kxf7 9. Qd5+ Ke8 10. Qxc5 d6 { 10...Qf6  11.Nxc3+- } 11. Qxc3 Nf6
{ 11...Qf6  Black would like to trade but White has more space, better development and needs to  keep his pieces on the board to attack.  12.e5  dxe5  If   12...Nxe5  then  13.Re1  for example  13...Kd8  14.Bg5  Nxf3+  15.Qxf3  Qxg5  16.Qf8+  Kd7  17.Qe8#  13.Bg5  Developing a piece with tempo by chasing the queen.  Qd6  14.Na3  Qb4  15.Qe3  White is attacking and should not trade pieces. White has a very strong attack. Black's king can no longer castle and is stuck in the middle. White has 4 pieces developed and Black only 2. Pawn e5 will fall shortly. White has obvious moves to continue: Rfe1, Rad1  (finishing development)  Nxe5  (opening up the e-file to attack Black's king)  . }
12. Re1
{ With the threat of e5. Black's king is vulnerable. For example  12...Bg4  13.e5+-  or   12...Kf7  13.Qb3++- }
*

