1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Bc5 6. d4 exd4 7. O-O d6 8.
cxd4 Bb6 9. d5
{ The objectively best move in this position is perhaps  9.Nc3  , maintaining the tension. This is the choice in the Master's Guide Chapter 4   The proposed move  9.d5  leads to equality in case of best play by Black, but in 65% of the cases Black plays the suboptimal  9...Ne5  and White gets a strong initiative }
9... Ne5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Ba3 { Preventing Black from castling. } 11... Bd4
{ Going for winning the exchange  (Ra1 against Bd4)  .   11...Ne7  12.Nd2  O-O  13.Qh5  Bd4  14.Rac1+-   11...Qf6  12.Nd2  Ne7  13.Kh1  O-O  14.Qb3±  with the idea of  f4  opening up the position. }
12. Nd2 Bxa1 13. Qxa1 f6
{ After  13...Qf6  , White is winning after  14.f4  exf4  15.Bb2  and the rook on  h8  is lost after the subsequent Bxg7 }
14. f4 exf4 15. e5
{ White's attack is completely crushing.  SF14:+8; depth 30  Black can resign. }
*

