1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 d6 7. Qb3 Qe7 8. d5
Nd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. O-O
{ Threatening to win the Ba5 with Qa4+ or Qb5+. Qa4+ directly is too dangerous:   10.Qa4+  Kd8  11.Qxa5  Qxe4+  12.Kd2   12.Kf1  d3-+  12...Bf5  13.Na3  Qxg2  14.Re1   14.Rf1  d3-+  14...Nf6-+ }
10... Bb6 { 10...Bxc3  11.Nxc3  dxc3  12.Ba3  followed by e5  (+3 SF12)  . }
11. e5
{ Opening up the position to attack the black king who is still in the middle. }
11... dxe5
{ If   11...Qxe5  then  12.Nd2  followed by Nf3 and Re1. This is a trainable variation in the Evans Gambit - Master's Guide: Accepted 5... Ba5 6... d6 7... Qe7 11... Qxe5  If   11...Bd7  then  12.a4  threatening a5 trapping the bishop on b6. After  12...a5  13.exd6  White is winning as Black has to take back with his queen on d6  (after cxd6 the bishop on b6 is hanging)  (.) }
12. Ba3 Qf6 13. cxd4 Bxd4 14. Nd2 Bxa1 15. Rxa1
{ White has a winning attack SF15:+4  Which ideas does White have?  - Ne4 in combination with d6  - Bb5+ followed by Bd7 Bxd7 Kxd7 Qxb7 Rc8 and then Ne4-Nc5 and Rc1  - Rc1 to increase pressure on c7  - Qb4 to threaten Qf8 or  (if the Black knight moves)  Ne4 Qe7  - d6 attacking f7 with Bc4 and Qb3  (after Black's queen moves)   - Qg3 attacking e5 and g7  (after Black's queen moves)   Which ideas we use depends on how Black continues:    15...Ne7  16.d6  followed by Ne4   15...Bd7  16.Qxb7  Rc8  17.Bb5  Qd8  18.Nc4  SF15:+6   15...Qb6  16.Qg3  double attack - do not trade when you are attacking!   15...b6  16.Ne4  Qd8  Qg3 }
*

