1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 d6 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. O-O
Bb6 9. Nbd2 Na5
{ 9...Nf6  10.dxe5   10...dxe5  11.Ba3  Na5  12.Qc2  Nxc4  13.Nxc4  attacking pawn e5 twofold is also comfortable  Nxe5  11.Nxe5  dxe5  11.Ba3  and White is winning.     Winning the pawn on d4 takes too much time  9...exd4  10.cxd4  Nxd4   If  10...Bxd4  then  11.Nxd4  Nxd4  12.Qg3  f6  13.a4  Qg4  14.Qc3  Nc6  15.f4±  (SF14:+2 depth 30)  11.Nxd4  Bxd4  12.Rb1  Nf6  13.Nf3  Bb6  14.e5+-  SF14:+2 depth 30 }
10. Qc2 Nxc4
{ The recommendation by GM Larry Kaufman is his New Repertoire for Black and White   10...f6  is covered in the  Evans Gambit - Master's Guide:  Accepted 5... Ba5 6... d6 7... Qd7 10... f6 }
11. Nxc4 exd4
{ 11...Qc6  12.Nxb6  axb6  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.Nxe5=    This is a trainable variation in the Evans Gambit Master's Guide: Accepted 5... Ba5 6... d6 7... Qd7 11... Qc6 }
12. cxd4 Ne7
{ The only other move besides  12...Ne7  that has been played is  12...Nf6  . The disadvantage of Nf6 is that e5 comes with tempo and the a3-f8 is not covered. White wins after  13.a4  threatening to trap Bb6  13...a5  14.Ba3  O-O  15.Bxd6  and after  15...cxd6  16.Nxb6 }
13. a4 c6 { 13...a6  14.Nxb6  cxb6  15.d5± } 14. Ba3 Bc7 15. e5
{ 15...d5  16.Nd6+  Bxd6  17.exd6  Ng6  18.Rfe1++-   15...dxe5  16.Rfe1  O-O  17.Ncxe5± }
