1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 exd4 7. O-O Nf6
{ 7...d6  8.Qb3  Qe7   8...Qf6  9.cxd4  Bb6   9...Nge7  10.e5  dxe5  11.d5+-  e4  12.Bb2  Qf4  13.Nfd2+-  10.Bb5  Bd7  11.Bg5±  9.e5  dxe5   9...Nxe5  10.Nxe5  Qxe5   10...dxe5  11.Qb5++-  11.Bxf7+  Kf8  12.cxd4  Qxd4  13.Bb2⩲  10.cxd4  exd4   10...e4  11.Ne5+-  11.Nbd2  Qf6  12.Ne4+-   In the Master's Guide, there are 2 trainable variations after 7... d6 8. Qb3: 8... Qe7 and 8... Qf6 }
8. Ba3
{ Preventing castling by Black. White often plays   8.e5  d5  which is not bad but Black scores 53%. After 8. Ba3, White scores 57% and Black 37% in rapid and classical games on Lichess. }
8... d6 { 8...Nxe4  9.Bd5  f5  10.Re1+-   8...dxc3  9.Qb3± } 9. e5 dxe5
{ 9...Ne4  10.exd6  cxd6  11.Qe2  d5  12.Nxd4  Nxd4  13.cxd4=  After   9...d5  , White should continue  10.Bb5  Ne4  11.Qa4  (threatening Bxc6 - Qxa5 and Bxc6 - Qxc6)  11...Bxc3  12.Nxc3  Nxc3  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.Qc2  and White is better. }
10. Qb3 { Attacking f7. } 10... Qd7 11. Re1
{ And White is winning.   11...e4  12.Nbd2  and the e-pawn falls. } *

