[White "3. Accepted 5... Be7 and 5... Bd6"]
[Black "Accepted 5... Be7 6... Na5 7... exd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Be7 6. d4 Na5 7. Be2 exd4 8.
Qxd4
{ Kasparov beat Anand with this variation in 1995 in the Riga Tal memorial  (see model games)  . Subsequently, Shirov used it to beat Timman and Short beat Sokolov and Georgiev with this line. So definitely GM tested and approved! }
8... Nf6
{ 8...Bf6  9.e5  Nc6  10.Qd5  Nge7  11.Qe4  d5  12.Qa4+-  Trapping the bishop on f6   8...d5  9.Qxg7  Bf6  10.Qg3  dxe4  11.Nd4=   8...d6  This is a trainable line in the Evans Gambit Master's Guide: Accepted 5... Be7 6... Na5 8... d6  9.Qxg7  Bf6  10.Qg3  Qe7  11.O-O  Qxe4  12.Re1= }
9. e5 Nc6 10. Qh4 Nd5 11. Qg3 g6
{ 11...O-O  is covered in the Evans Gambit - Master's Guide: Accepted 5... Be7 6... Na5 7... exd4 11... 0-0 and transposes after  12.Bh6  g6  13.O-O  I recommend not taking the exchange as White's initiative and space advantage are worth more than the exchange. After Bxf8, Black has compensation: pawn, bishop pair, and lack of development of White's queenside.  13...Re8  14.Ng5 }
12. O-O O-O 13. Bh6 Re8 14. Ng5
{ White has the initiative in exchange for one pawn. Black has difficulty completing his development. The immediate threat of White is Bc4 attacking Nd5 and indirectly f7. If Black plays Nb6 to prevent Bc4, then White will just complete his development with Nbd2 and Rad1 with ideas of Ne4 and f4 attacking Black's king. }
*

