[White "3. Accepted 5... Be7 and 5... Bd6"]
[Black "Accepted 5... Bd6 6... exd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Bd6
{ 5. Bd6 is played in 5% of the games  (Lichess - rapid and classical - all ratings)  .  The move Bd6 fortifies the defence of pawn e5 but hinders Black's natural development.   White will complete his development, protect pawn e4 and then pressure e5 and Bd6 through Nbd2-c4. }
6. d4 exd4
{ This is the Bd6-variation that is most played at Lichess 1600-1800 level. }
7. O-O dxc3
{ 7...Nge7  8.Ng5  Ne5  9.Bb3  h6  10.f4+-  SF14:+4-depth 30   7...Nf6  8.e5  Nxe5  9.Nxe5  Bxe5  10.Re1+-  SF14:+3-depth 30 }
8. Nxc3 Ne5
{ 8...Be5  9.Bxf7+  Kxf7  10.Qd5+  Kf8  11.Nxe5+-  SF14:+5-depth 30     8...Nf6  9.e5  Bxe5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Re1  d6  12.f4  winning a piece }
9. Nxe5 Bxe5 10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Qd5+ Kf6 12. f4 Bxc3 13. Qg5+
{ Winning Qd8  SF14:+5-depth 30 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Accepted 5... Be7 and 5... Bd6"]
[Black "Accepted 5... Bd6 6... Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Bd6
{ Bd6 is played in 5% of the games  (Lichess - rapid and classical - all ratings)  .  Bd6 fortifies the defence of pawn e5 but hinders black's natural development.   White will complete his development, protect pawn e4 and then pressure e5 and Bd6 through Nbd2-c4. }
6. d4 Nf6 7. O-O O-O
{ If Black takes the pawn:  7...Nxe4  then  8.dxe5  Nxe5  9.Nxe5  Bxe5  10.Qd5  with a double attack on  f7  (mate)  and  Ne4  . After  10...Qe7  , White plays  11.Re1  and if  11...Bxh2  then  12.Kf1  and White wins. }
8. Re1 { Protecting pawn e4. } 8... h6
{ Preventing the pin with Bg5. Alternatives are:   8...b6  trainable in the Evans Gambit Masters Guide: Accepted 5... Bd6 8... b6  9.Bg5  h6  10.Bh4  Bb7  11.Bd5  Be7  12.Bxf6  Bxf6  13.dxe5  Be7  14.Nbd2  with equality.   8...Re8  9.Ng5  Re7  10.f4  h6  11.dxe5+- }
9. Nbd2 Re8 10. Qb3 Qe7 11. a4
{ Many players will question why it is OK to give up Bc4. It is not about the pieces that leave the board but about the pieces that remain on the board. Nf3, Nc4, and the pawn on d4 are going to exert a lot of pressure on e5. }
11... Na5 12. Qa2 Nxc4 13. Nxc4
{ White is slightly better. White threatens to take e5 and is better developed. On   13...exd4  White continues  14.e5  and White is better  (SF14:+2-depth 30)  . Please note that White is not threatening to play exd6 or exf6 immediately because of Qxe1 Nxe1 Rxe1 back rank mate. But the threat is first Bxh6 followed by exf6 and White wins. }
*

