[White "4. Declined and early deviations"]
[Black "Declined - 5... a6 6... d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bb6
{ Black declines the gambit in 13% of the games  (Lichess, rapid and classical, all ratings) }
5. a4 a6
{ If  5...Nf6  then  6.a5  Bd4  7.c3  trapping the bishop. Black can get two pawns with Bxf2 followed by Nxe4 but that is insufficient compensation for the bishop.   5...Nxb4  6.a5  Bc5  7.c3  Nc6  8.O-O  Nf6  9.d4  is covered in the Evans Gambit Master's Guide:Declined 5. .. a6 6... Nf6 7... d6 }
6. Nc3 d6 { 6...Nxb4  7.Nxe5  Qf6  8.Nf3  and white is better. } 7. Nd5 Ba7
{ Otherwise, White will take the bishop and damage black's pawn structure.   7...Nf6  8.Nxb6  is a trainable variation in the Evans Gambit Master's Guide Declined 5. .. a6 6... Nf6 7... d6 }
8. d3 h6
{ Preventing Bg5. After  8...Nf6  White continues  9.Bg5  h6  10.Bxf6  gxf6  and White is better. Black's king structure has been damaged and White will attack with Nh4-Qh5-Nf5 ideas  11.Nh4  Be6  12.c3+-   If Black pins the knight on f3 with  8...Bg4  then White continues  9.h3  Bh5  10.b5⩲ }
9. O-O Nf6
{ 9...Bg4  10.h3  Bh5  11.b5  Nd4   11...Na5  12.Ba2  c6  13.bxc6  Nxc6  14.Rb1  Rb8±  SF14:+2-depth 30  12.g4  Nxf3+  13.Qxf3  Bg6  14.bxa6  bxa6±  SF14:+2-depth 30 }
10. b5 axb5
{ 10...Ne7  11.Nxf6+  gxf6±   10...Nd4  11.bxa6  bxa6  12.Nxd4  Bxd4  13.c3  Ba7  14.Nxf6+  Qxf6  15.Bd5± }
11. axb5 Bxf2+
{ Discovered attack on Ra1. White gets Bishop + Knight against Rook + pawn. }
12. Rxf2 Rxa1 13. Nxf6+ { Otherwise Black has the unpleasant Ng4. } 13... Qxf6
14. bxc6 { And White is much better  (SF14:+3-depth 30)  . } *

